column19: 2.1 miles east of Fakahatchee Boardwalk on US41, attempting to cross road from north to south.
column33: Time: 22:29 ET (10:29pm)   About four feet of the snake's anterior visible from guardrail out onto road, head positioned over white stripe on north side of hwy.  I was going 52mph and immediately slowed down, but car was behind me.  I turned around to go back but I believe the combination of two cars in a row passing directly in front of the snake spooked it back towards canal because it wasn't there when I went back.  Slowly made three passes and didn't see it again..I'm a field zoologist and this is my 5th python sighting (3rd one alive), so please don't think I'm reporting a cottonmouth.  It was a python, LARGE, and I believe Burmese (can't positively say it wasn't a rock python, but I know Burmese are common in that area).  One roadkill I measured in the past was 9' and this one looked bigger than the 9' one.  I conservatively estimate it was 10' in length since I saw approx. 4' of the snake, and that 4' included its head-thru-lung-area of body, but couldn't see the rest of it (behind guardrail).

column19: Dead on road. Observed on the south side of I-75 between Florida Panther National Wildlife Refuge and Picayune Strand State Forest. Snake was in the emergency lane.  Location of snake was approximately 250 feet east of the emergency median crossing.
column33: Snake was already putrid when discovered at 1414, and likely got hit during the evening of 09/25/2019. Internal organs had been forced out of cloaca and wounds created by vehicle(s) crushing it. Total length was 95.75 inches and snout-vent length was 81.13 inches. Small spurs and relatively skinny body.  Perhaps female, but not confident. Interestingly, I saw an otter dive into the canal on the south side of I-75 when I turned my vehicle into the guard rail opening in order to drive to the snake's location.
